  Introduction to The World Wide Web & HTML  
  2.1 What Is The World Wide Web?  
 

HTML Element and Attribute References

!-- --   Comment

Syntax    <!-- -->

Comments are ignored by the HTML parser. All text between the beginning of the comment (<!--) and the end of the comment (-->) is ignored. White space is allowed within the comment but not between the opening <!-- and closing -->. Both the start and end tags are required. A common error is to include a string of hyphens ("---") within a comment. Authors should avoid putting two or more adjacent hyphens inside comments.

!DOCTYPE - Specifies the DTD the document corresponds to

Syntax    <!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD [+ DTD VERSION HERE]//EN">

A valid HTML document declares what version of HTML is used in the document. The document type declaration names the document type definition (DTD) in use for the document. HTML 4.01 specifies three DTDs, so authors must include one of the following document type declarations in their documents. The DTDs vary in the elements they support.

(1) HTML 4.01 Strict

The HTML 4.01 Strict DTD includes all elements and attributes that have not been deprecated or do not appear in frameset documents. Deprecated elements and attributes (including most presentational attributes), frames, and link targets are not allowed in HTML 4.01 Strict.

The document type declaration for HTML 4.01 Strict is

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01//EN">

(2) HTML 4.01 Transitional

The HTML 4.01 Transitional DTD includes everything in the strict DTD plus deprecated elements and attributes (most of which concern visual presentation).

The document type declaration for HTML 4.01 Transitional is

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">

(3) HTML 4.01 Frameset

The HTML 4.01 Frameset DTD includes everything in the transitional DTD plus frames as well.

The document type declaration for HTML 4.01 Frameset is

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Frameset//EN">

a - Anchor

Syntax    <a>...</a>

Attributes

·    accesskey=character (accessibility key character)

·    href=uri (uri for linked resource)

·    class=className

·    charset=charset (character encoding of linked resource)

·    type=ContentType (advisory content type)

·    name (named link destination)

·    hreflang=LanguageCode (language code)

·    rel=LinkTypes (forward link types)

·    rev=LinkTypes (reverse link types)

·    shape=Shape (for use with client-side image maps)

·    coords=Coords (for use with client-side image maps)

·    onfocus=Script (the element got the focus)

·    onblur=Script (the element lost the focus)

Intrinsic Events

·    onfocus,

 onblur,

 onclick,

 ondblclick,

 onmousedown,

 onmouseup,

 onmouseover,


onmousemove,

 onmouseout,

 onkeypress,

 onkeydown,

 onkeyup

Anchor elements designate the start or destination of a hypertext link. The anchor element requires the href= attribute or the id= and name= attributes to be specified (use both the id= and name= attributes together for backward compatibility).

The applet element is used to embed Java applets. It has been deprecated

in favor of the object element. However, since the few browsers that support the object element do so with significant bugs, applet is currently a more reliable method of embedding Java applets.

base - Document Base URI (Universal Resource Identifier)

Syntax    <base>

Attributes

·    href=uri (uri for linked resource)

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    lang=string

·    language=javascript | jscript | vbs | vbscript

·    target=frame-target

·    title=string

The base element defines the document's base URI for resolving relative URIs (Universal Resource Identifiers) contained within the document. A document cannot contain more than one base element and must appear in the head section, prior to any elements that include a partial URI.

basefont - Base Font Size

Syntax    <basefont>

Attributes

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    lang=string

·    style=string

·    title=string

·    size=string (font size adjustment)

·    color=color (font color adjustment)

·    face=string (font face adjustment)

The basefont element sets the base font size (using the size attribute). Font size changes achieved with font are relative to the base font size set by basefont. If basefont is not used, the default base font size is 3.

Buttons created with the button element function just like buttons created with the input element, but they offer richer rendering possibilities: the button element may have content. For example, a button element that contains an image functions like and may resemble an input element whose type is set to "image", but the button element type allows content. Visual user agents may render button buttons with relief and an up/down motion when clicked, while they may render input buttons as "flat" images.

The col element allows authors to group together attribute specifications for table columns. The col does not group columns together structurally, that's the role of the colgroup element. col elements are empty and serve only as a support for attributes. They may appear inside or outside an explicit column group (i.e., colgroup element).

colgroup - Table Column Group

Syntax    <colgroup>...</colgroup>

Attributes

·    align=center | left | right

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    span=number (col attributes affect N columns)

·    width

=multi-length (column width specification)

·    style=string

·    title=string

·    valign=baseline | bottom | middle | top

 ondblclick,

 onmousedown,

 onmouseup,

 onmouseover,


onmousemove,

 onmouseout,

 onkeypress,

 onkeydown,

 onkeyup

The colgroup element creates an explicit column group. The number of columns in the column group may be specified in two, mutually exclusive ways:

1. The element's span attribute (default value 1) specifies the number of columns in the group.

2. Each col element in the colgroup represents one or more columns in the group.

The advantage of using the span attribute is that authors may group together information about column widths.

The dir element has been deprecated.

deprecated:- A deprecated element or attribute is one that has been outdated by newer constructs. Deprecated elements may become obsolete in future versions of HTML.

The dir element was designed to be used for creating multicolumn directory lists. The menu element was designed to be used for single column menu lists. Both elements have the same structure as ul, just different rendering. In practice, a user agent will render a dir or menu list exactly as a ul list.

It is strongly recommended that you use ul instead of these elements.

The div and span elements, in conjunction with the id and class attributes, offer a generic mechanism for adding structure to documents. These elements define content to be inline (span) or block-level (div) but impose no other presentational styles on the content. Thus, authors may use these elements in conjunction with style sheets, the lang attribute, etc., to tailor HTML to their own needs and tastes.

dl denotes a definition list. A definition list (dl) varies only slightly from other types of lists in that list items consist of two parts: a term and a description. The definition term (dt) is given by the dt element and is restricted to inline content. The definition description (dd) is given with a dd element that contains block-level content.

The fieldset element allows authors to group related controls and labels. Grouping controls makes it easier for users to understand their purpose while simultaneously facilitating tabbing navigation for visual user agents and speech navigation for speech-oriented user agents. The proper use of this element makes documents more accessible. The legend element allows authors to assign a caption to a fieldset. The legend improves accessibility when the fieldset is rendered non-visually.

Syntax    <font>...</font>

·    face=string

·    size=number

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    lang=string

·    language=javascript | jscript | vbs | vbscript

·    style=string

·    title=string

The font element changes the font size and color for text in its contents.
The basefont element sets the base font size (using the size attribute). Font size changes achieved with font are relative to the base font size set by basefont. If basefont is not used, the default base font size is 3.

Syntax    <form>...</form>

Attributes

·    action=uri (server-side form handler)

·    method=get | post (HTTP method used to submit the form)

·    enctype=string

·    accept=content-type-list (list of MIME types for file upload)

·    name=string (name of form for scripting)

·    target=string

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    lang=string

·    language=javascript | jscript | vbs | vbscript

·    style=string

·    title=string

Intrinsic Events

·    onsubmit,

 onreset,

 onclick,

 ondblclick,

 onmousedown,

 onmouseup,

 onmouseover,


onmousemove,

 onmouseout,

 onkeypress,

 onkeydown,

 onkeyup

The form element acts as a container for controls. It specifies:

1. The layout of the form (given by the contents of the element).

2. The program that will handle the completed and submitted form (the action attribute). The receiving program must be able to parse name/value pairs in order to make use of them.

3. The method by which user data will be sent to the server (the method attribute).

4. A character encoding that must be accepted by the server in order to handle this form (the accept-charset attribute).

A form can contain text and markup (paragraphs, lists, etc.) in addition to form controls.

frame - Subwindow

Syntax    <frame>

Attributes

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    style=string

·    title=string

·    name=window_name | _blank | _parent | _self | _top (name of frame for targetting)

·    longdesc=uri (link to long description - complements title)

·    src=uri (source of frame content)

·    frameborder=1|0 (request for frame borders)

·    marginwidth=numeric value (margin width in pixels)

·    marginheight=numeric value (margin height in pixels)

·    noresize=noresize|resize [allow users to resize frames]

·    scrolling=yes|no|auto (scrollbar or no scrollbar)

The frame element defines the contents and appearance of a single frame within a frameset.

frameset - Window Subdivision

Syntax    <frameset>...</frameset>

Attributes

·    rows

=multi-length (list of lengths, default: 100% [1 row])

·    cols

=multi-length (list of lengths, default: 100% [1 row])

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    style=string

·    title=string

Intrinsic Events

onload,

 onunload

The frameset element specifies the layout of the main user window in terms of rectangular subspaces.

Setting the rows attribute defines the number of horizontal subspaces in a frameset. Setting the cols attribute defines the number of vertical subspaces. Both attributes may be set simultaneously to create a grid.

If the rows attribute is not set, each column extends the entire length of the page. If the cols attribute is not set, each row extends the entire width of the page. If neither attribute is set, the frame takes up exactly the size of the page.

Frames are created left-to-right for columns and top-to-bottom for rows. When both attributes are specified, views are created left-to-right in the top row, left-to-right in the second row, etc.

head - Document Head

Syntax    <head>...</head>

Valid elements in head block:

·    base

·    link

·    title

·    meta

·    basefont

·    bgsound

The head provides information that does not affect the rendering of the document, but may be of use to the browser. The head falls before the body of the document is specified. The above elements are valid in the head block.

iframe - Inline Subwindow

Syntax    <iframe>...</iframe>

Attributes

·    class=className

·    id=string

·    name=window_name | _blank | _parent | _self | _top (name of frame for targetting)

·    src=uri (source of frame content)

·    longdesc=uri (link to long description - complements title)

·    frameborder=1|0 (request for frame borders)

·    marginwidth=pixels (margin widths in pixels)

·    marginheight=pixels (margin height in pixels)

·    scrolling=yes|no|auto (scrollbar or no scrollbar)

·    align=bottom|middle|top|left|right (vertical or horizontal alignment)

·    height=

multi-length (frame height)

·    width=

multi-length (frame width)

·    style=string

·    title=string

The iframe element allows authors to insert a frame within a block of text. Inserting an inline frame within a section of text is much like inserting an object via the object element: they both allow you to insert an HTML document in the middle of another, they may both be aligned with surrounding text, etc.

The information to be inserted inline is designated by the src attribute of this element. The contents of the iframe element, on the other hand, should only be displayed by user agents that do not support frames or are configured not to display frames.

Inline frames may not be resized and thus they do not support the noresize attribute.

noframes - Alternate Content Container for Non-Frame-based Rendering

Syntax    <noframes>...</noframes>

Attributes

·    id=string

·    style=string

·    title=string

Intrinsic Events

·    onclick,

 ondblclick,

 onmousedown,

 onmouseup,

onmousemove,

 onmouseout,

 onkeypress,

 onkeydown,

 onkeyup

The noframes element specifies content that should be displayed only by user agents that do not support frames or are configured not to display frames. User agents that support frames must only display the contents of a noframes declaration when configured not to display frames. User agents that do not support frames must display the contents of noframes in any case.

The noframes element is part of both the transitional and frameset DTDs. In a document that uses the frameset DTD, noframes may be used at the end of the frameset section of the document.

noscript - Alternate Content Container for Non-Script-based Rendering

Syntax    <noscript>...</noscript>

The noscript element allows authors to provide alternate content when a script is not executed. The content of a noscript element should only be rendered by a script-aware user agent in the following cases:

·    The user agent is configured not to evaluate scripts.

·    The user agent doesn't support a scripting language invoked by a script element earlier in the document.

User agents that do not support client-side scripts must render this element's contents.

The pre element tells visual user agents that the enclosed text is "preformatted". When handling preformatted text, visual user agents:

·    May leave white space intact.

·    May render text with a fixed-pitch font.

·    May disable automatic word wrap.

·    Must not disable bidirectional processing.

Non-visual user agents are not required to respect extra white space in the content of a pre element.

title - Document Title

Syntax    <title>...</title>

Attributes

·    lang=string

Every HTML document must have a title element in the head section. You should use the title element to identify the contents of a document using appropriate keywords within a concise sentence.
